The field of ILD includes a plethora of different, individual conditions that exhibit varying expected prognoses and disease courses. The most common ILD is IPF. IPF affects approximately 3 million people worldwide, with incidence increasing dramatically with age, it has a reported median survival of approximately 3 years from the time of diagnosis.82 Age is the strongest demographic risk factor for IPF, suggesting that “accelerated” lung aging is a driving force for its development.83 The pathogenesis of IPF development is an area of much debate. A sequence of three pathophysiologic stages has been described (see Table 6.2
).83
However, it is important to clarify that not all individuals in the predisposition stage will go on to exhibit clinically detectable disease. Similarly, not all patients with IPF develop all stages in a sequential order before established disease is detected.
